In the entire history of the United States only fifteen people have been convicted of Treason, and only a few more than that have been indicted for this specific crime. Treason is the only crime clearly described in the Constitution and for two centuries federal courts have had a very consistent definition of what constitutes Treason. To be convicted of Treason a US resident has to make war against the US, or give aid and comfort to an â€œenemyâ€. The courts have had a consistent definition of the term â€œenemyâ€ to only include entities involved is a hostile, armed, conflict with the United States. Only one American has been charged with Treason in the Post WWII era, Adam Yahiye Gadahn, who joined al-Qaeda and became a recruiter and Internet spokesman. He was killed in a drone strike in 2015 and never brought to trial.

